Docker Notes (14/03/2026)
Objective: Run a CentOS container using Docker.

Step 1: Access Docker Hub
Go to Docker Hub.

Search for CentOS.

Select CentOS 7.9.2009.

Step 2: Run CentOS Container
Open the terminal.

Type:

bash
docker run centos:7
Check running containers:

bash
docker ps
(Shows container ID, image, command, status, ports, names — if not running, proceed below.)

Step 3: Interactive Mode
Run interactively:

bash
docker run -it centos:7 bash
Inside the container, check release info:

bash
cat /etc/*release*
Exit the container:

bash
exit
Step 4: Detached Mode
Check containers again:

bash
docker ps
Run container in detached mode for 20 seconds:

bash
docker run -d centos:7 sleep 20
(This command runs for 20 seconds and then stops.)

Docker Notes (Continuation)
Checking Containers
bash
docker ps -a
bash
docker run -d centos:7
This container may exit naturally — the computer stops it automatically (“natural death”).

Running a Long Process
bash
docker run -d centos:7 sleep 2000
bash
docker ps
(Shows running containers.)

Stopping a Container
To terminate a running container:

bash
docker stop <container_name>
Example:

bash
docker stop trusting_noether
After stopping, check:

bash
docker ps -a
Status will show “Exited 136” — meaning it stopped before completion.

Deleting Containers
Delete by ID:

bash
docker rm <container_id>
Example:

bash
docker rm 518...
Delete by Name:

bash
docker rm <container_name>
Example:

bash
docker rm zen_habit

Removing Containers
Check all containers:

bash
docker ps -a
File is deleted — out of 6 files, only 5 remain.

Removing Multiple Containers
Sometimes we need to remove a large number of containers, and doing it one by one takes time.
You can remove several at once using partial IDs:

bash
docker rm <first_3_letters_of_ID>
Example:

bash
docker rm acd pna dad
Outcome: these three containers will be deleted.

Verify Deletion
Check again:

bash
docker ps -a
Checking Images
To see or verify if you have images:
bash
docker image

Docker Lesson (27/03/2026)
Pulling and Running an Image
Pull the Hello-world image:

bash
docker pull hello-world
(This downloads the image from Docker Hub.)
Run the image:
bash
docker run hello-world
(This executes the pulled image.)

Checking Images
List all available images:

bash
docker images
Removing an Image
To remove an image:
bash
docker rmi <image_name>
(Example: docker rmi hello-world)

Note:  
You can’t remove the image if it’s still being used by a container.
First, you need to delete the container that’s using it.

Command Prompts
Checking Containers
bash
docker ps -a
Lists all containers (active and inactive) and helps get the container ID.

Executing Commands Inside a Container
bash
docker exec <container_ID> cat /etc/os-release
Used to get information from a container without directly entering it.  
Works only with active containers.

Additional Notes
You can also check if the container is running before executing commands.

Example command to view OS details inside a container:
bash
cat /etc/os-release
Docker Version
bash
docker --version
Displays the installed Docker version.

Running Containers in Detached Mode
bash
docker run -d <container_ID>
or

bash
docker run -d <container_name>
Runs the container in the background (detached mode).

Stopping a Container
bash
docker stop redis
Stops the container named “redis”.

