Docker Notes (3/4/2026)
Viewing Detailed Container Information
To get everything in detail (including “info junk”):

bash
docker ps -la
Displays detailed information about all containers.

Managing Terminals
To exit a running container:
Ctrl + C

To open a duplicate terminal/host:
Command + T

Container Identification
CID → Container ID in Docker.

Task: Create a Timer
Goal: Display the current date and time, updating every second.

Command:

bash
docker run -it ubuntu bash -c "while true; do date; sleep 1; done"
Explanation:

docker run -it ubuntu bash -c → Runs an interactive Ubuntu container.

while true → Keeps the loop running forever.

date → Displays the current date and time.

sleep 1 → Waits one second before repeating.

The output updates every second continuously.

Docker Notes — Alpine Linux
Overview
Alpine → A small, lightweight Linux distribution often used in Docker containers.

sh -c → Runs a shell command or script inside the terminal.

While loop → Used to run commands continuously (forever).

Key Concepts
Fractional / Run time / Compile time → Different stages of program execution and building.
(Run time: when the program executes; Compile time: when the code is translated into machine code.)

Checking Alpine Version
Go to Docker Hub and check the version of Alpine.

Pull the Alpine image:
bash
docker pull alpine
Check Docker version:
bash
docker --version
(Used to verify Docker installation and version.)

Modes of Operation
Mode	Description
Detached mode	Runs the container in the background.
Attached mode	Runs the container in the foreground (you cannot use the terminal freely).

Docker Notes — Attached & Detached Mode
Steps Demonstrated
Run a container in detached mode:
bash
docker run -d alpine sleep 1000
Check containers:
bash
docker ps -a
Open a new terminal.

Stop the container:
bash
docker stop Obd08398Fbbd
Explanation
When you stop the container from another terminal, the original terminal shows that the container has stopped.

This demonstrates the difference between attached and detached modes:
Detached mode → Container runs in the background.
Attached mode → Container runs in the foreground (you interact directly with it).

Jenkins Overview
Jenkins is a tool that automatically builds, tests, and delivers your code.
You don’t have to do it manually every time the codebase changes.

Jenkins doesn’t handle deployment — it focuses on delivery.

🌐 IP Address vs MAC Address
Concept	Description	Analogy
IP Address	Internet Protocol — digital identity that can change.	Like your home address (changes when you move).
MAC Address	Media Access Control — unique hardware identifier that never changes.	Like a fingerprint (constant).


Gateway → The route connecting your local network to external networks.

Building a Jenkins Container in Docker

Run Jenkins container:

bash
docker run jenkins/jenkins:latest
Verify successful setup:

Open Docker Desktop → check if Jenkins appears under containers.

Jenkins server runs on Port 8080.

Inspect container details:

bash
docker inspect <container_ID>
IP Address: 172.17.0.2

Gateway: 172.17.0.1

Installing Flask
Steps to create and set up a Flask app:

bash
mkdir my_flask_app
cd my_flask_app
py -m venv venv
venv\Scripts\activate
pip install flask

