Data Persistence
Definition:  
Refers to the practice of storing data in a non‑volatile storage medium — meaning the data remains intact and accessible even after:

An application is closed

A computer is turned off

Or a system fails

Volatile vs Non‑Volatile Storage
Type	Description	Example
Volatile	Temporary storage that loses data when power is off	RAM (Random Access Memory)
Non‑Volatile	Permanent storage that retains data even after shutdown	Hard drive, SSD


Key Concepts
RAM → Temporary, volatile memory.

Data persistence ensures data moves from temporary (RAM) to non‑volatile storage for long‑term retention.

SSD (Solid‑State Drive) → Used to make data persistent.

Data Persistence and Docker Volumes
Concept Recap
Data stored in volatile memory (RAM) is lost when power is off.

Persistent data remains until explicitly deleted or cleared.

To make Docker container configurations persistent, we store data locally.

Setting Up Persistent Jenkins Data
Step 1: Create a Local Directory
Create a directory on your computer/laptop to store Jenkins data:

bash
mkdir my-jenkins-data
(You can name it anything, e.g., my-bank-data.)

Step 2: Run Jenkins Container with Volume Mapping
Run Jenkins and link the local directory to the container:

bash
docker run -p 8080:8080 -v my-jenkins-data:/var/jenkins_home 

Pip — Python Package Manager
Definition:  
Pip is a package manager for Python, a tool that manages and installs extra Python code (libraries and packages).
It’s like a Python app store — you use it to download and manage Python modules.

Pip Tasks
Installs Python libraries and packages.

The name “Pip” stands for “Pip Installs Packages.”

It’s a tool inside a package — used to add functionality to Python projects.

Installing Flask
To install Flask using Pip:

bash
python3 -m pip install flask
Explanation:

The -m flag tells Python to run a module as a program.

Instead of running a file, Python finds the module (pip) and executes it directly.

This command installs Flask globally or in your virtual environment.

How to Build a Docker Image (By Yourself)
Steps Overview
Create a file — this will serve as the foundation for your Docker image.

Start a web server — to host or deploy that local file.

Create a directory for your project:

bash
mkdir myapp
(This command makes a new folder named myapp on your computer.)

Understanding Command Structure
Every command has three parts:

Part	Description	Example
Command	The main action you want to perform	mkdir
Flag	Extra instruction that modifies the command’s behavior	-p (creates parent directories if needed)
Argument	The target or item the command acts on	myapp


So, the full command:

bash
mkdir -p myapp
means “create a directory named myapp, including any missing parent folders.”

Flags Explained
A flag is an additional option that changes how a command works.

It’s like a special setting that tells the command to perform a specific action.

Example:

bash
mkdir -p myapp
Here, -p ensures the command doesn’t fail if parent directories don’t exist.

Running a Python App
Step 1: Create a Directory
To create a new folder for your app:

bash
mkdir -p ~/myapp
This command creates a directory named myapp.

Step 2: Navigate Inside the Directory
Move into the newly created folder:

bash
cd ~/myapp
Step 3: Run the Python File
Run your Python application depending on your operating system:

Operating System	Command	Notes
macOS / Linux	python3 app.py	Uses Python 3 explicitly.
Windows	python app.py	Works with default Python installation. 

Building and Running a Docker Image
🧩 Step 1: Create a Dockerfile
On Mac: use nano Dockerfile

On Windows: use Notepad to create a file named Dockerfile

This file defines how your Docker image will be built.

Step 2: Build the Docker Image
Run the following command:

bash
docker build -t flaskapp .
Explanation:

docker build → Command used to build Docker images.

-t flaskapp → Tags the image with the name flaskapp.

→ Refers to the current directory (where the Dockerfile is located).

This is the correct command to build your image.

Step 3: Run the Docker Container
After building, run your container:

bash
docker run -p 8080:9090 flaskapp
Explanation:

-p 8080:9090 → Maps host port 8080 to container port 9090.

flaskapp → The name of the image you just built.

This command starts the container and runs your Flask app.

Form (Foundation)
dockerfile
FROM <base‑image>
Defines the base image — the starting layer for your Docker image.
Examples: python:3.10, node:18, nginx, ubuntu, alpine.

2.Working Directory
dockerfile
WORKDIR <app‑directory>
Sets the directory inside the container where commands will run.

3.Copy Files
dockerfile
COPY <source> <destination>
Copies files from your local system into the container.

4.Run Dependencies
dockerfile
RUN <install‑dependencies>
Installs required packages or dependencies.

5.Expose Port
dockerfile
EXPOSE <port>
Specifies which port the container listens on.

6.Command to Run
dockerfile
CMD ["run", "app"]
Defines the command that starts your application when the container launches.

Note:  
The base image acts as the foundation layer — the prebuilt environment your Dockerfile builds upon.